ational Project -- tBuilding Broken Worlds: The Alien Franchise, Failed Utopias, and Other Bio-Shocks -- tAll That’s Left Is the Choosing: Rethinking Agency in Bioshock and Beyond -- tBranching Out: Narrative Decision Systems after Bioshock -- tThe Hands of the Other: Media Allegory in Bioshock and The Hands of Orlac -- tPlaying Your Role: Bioshock Infinite’s Burial at Sea and the Function of the Player -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe Bioshock series looms large in the industry and culture of video games for its ambitious incorporation of high-minded philosophical questions and retro-futuristic aesthetics into the ultraviolent first-person shooter genre. Beyond the Sea marks ten years since the release of the original game with an interdisciplinary collection of essays on Bioshock, Bioshock 2, and Bioshock Infinite. Simultaneously lauded as landmarks in the artistic growth of the medium and criticized for their compromised vision and politics, the Bioshock games have been the subject of significant scholarly and critical discussion. Moving past well-trodden debates, Beyond the Sea broadens the conversation by putting video games in dialogue with a diverse range of other disciplines and cultural forms, from parenting psychology to post-humanism, from Thomas Pynchon to German expressionist cinema. Offering bold new perspectives on a canonical series, Beyond the Sea is a timely contribution to our understanding of the aesthetics, the industry, and the culture of video games. Contributors include Daniel Ante-Contreras (Miracosta), Luke Arnott (Western Ontario), Betsy Brey (Waterloo), Patrick Brown (Iowa), Michael Fuchs (Graz), Jamie Henthorn (Catawba), Brendan Keogh (Queensland), Cameron Kunzelman (Georgia), Cody Mejeur (Michigan State), Matthew Thomas Payne (Notre Dame), Gareth Schott (Waikato), Karen Schrier (Marist), Sarah Stang (York/Ryerson), Sarah Thorne (Carleton), John Vanderhoef (California State, Dominguez Hills), Matthew Wysocki (Flagler), Jordan R. Youngblood (Eastern Connecticut State), and Sarah Zaidan (Emerson).  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Popular Culture.2bisacsh1 aAldred, Jessica, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAldred, Jessica, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aAnte-Contreras, Daniel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aArnott, Luke, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrey, Betsy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrown, Patrick, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFuchs, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHenthorn, Jamie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKeogh, Brendan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKunzelman, Cameron, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMejeur, Cody, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aParker, Felan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aParker, Felan, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aPayne, Matthew Thomas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSchott, Gareth, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSchrier, Karen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aStang, Sarah, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aThorne, Sarah, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aVanderhoef, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWys